Definition.WordDefinition:
Start-up \Start"-up`\ (st[aum]rt"[u^]p`), n. 1. One who comes suddenly into notice; an upstart. [Obs.] --Shak. [1913 Webster]
2. A kind of high rustic shoe. [Obs.] --Drayton. [1913 Webster]
A startuppe, or clownish shoe. --Spenser. [1913 Webster]

Dictionary.Name: The Collaborative International Dictionary of English v.0.44

Definition.WordDefinition: start up v 1: get going or set in motion; "We simply could not start the engine"; "start up the computer" [syn: {start}] [ant: {stop}] 2: get off the ground; "Who started this company?"; "We embarked on an exciting enterprise"; "I start my day with a good breakfast"; "We began the new semester"; "The afternoon session begins at 4 PM"; "The blood shed started when the partisans launched a surprise attack" [syn: {start}, {embark on}, {commence}]

startup n 1: the act of setting in operation; "repeated shutdowns and startups are expensive" 2: the act of starting a new operation or practice; "he opposed the inauguration of fluoridation"; "the startup of the new factory was delayed by strikes" [syn: {inauguration}]
